#Text=Christina Doreothea Stuart
#Text=Christina Doreothea Stuart , known under her stage name Madame Stuart ( died after 1774 ) , was a dancer , equilibrist , singer and musician active in Norway .
#Text=She played an important part in Norwegian cultural history ; she is noted as a pioneer figure of ballet in Norway and connected to the activity of the first public theater in Norway .
#Text=She is considered to be the first ballet dancer to perform in Oslo and Norway .
#Text=Life
#Text=The background of Christina Doreothea Stuart is unknown .
#Text=She was married to the famous British dancer and acrobat Michael Stuart in his third marriage , with whom she had several children .
#Text=He was known in Denmark since 1756 , and when he arrived in Oslo in Norway in 1769 , Christina arrived with him as his wife as well as his dance partner . [ 1 ]
#Text=Early career in Oslo
#Text=Stuart was not only a dancer , but also a singer and a musician .

#Text=In a performance in Oslo on 26 January 1770 , " The Great Virtuosis Madame Stuart " sang , played instrumental music , performed acrobatics and danced ballet , and in on 31 January 1771 , " The wellfamous Madame Stuart " performed tight-rope-walking . [ 1 ]
#Text=The Stuart couple are counted as pioneers of Norwegian ballet , and the performance of Madame Stuart has been called as the possibly first ballet ever performed in Oslo .
#Text=She became a popular and successful artist in Oslo , where there were no public theaters at the time and the only entertainment was offered by travelling artists passing through town .
#Text=She held her performances in the city hall , hosted charity concerts to the benefit of the poor , and composed songs in the Danish language . [ 1 ]
#Text=While her husband was admired for his skill as an artist , he was also notorious as a person because of his heavy drinking and fistfights .
#Text=While she performed , Michael opened and managed an inn where he sold wine , beer and sweets .

#Text=When he died in June 1771 , she was left with several small children to support and was reportedly in a grim financial situation , selling beer and different types of goods and clothing , as well as giving lessons in dance and continuing with her stage performances .
#Text=Companionship with Nürenbach
#Text=From October 1771 , she performed in companionship with the acrobat Martin Nürenbach from Sweden .
#Text=On 7 October 1771 , Stuart and Nürenbach performed ballet , acrobatics and tight-rope-walking .
#Text=Stuart sang an aria , and on the last scene , they performed as actors together .

#Text=Reportedly , the two demonstrated different kinds of positions and balancing , offering equilibrist feats : while Nürenbach twisted his body into different shapes and forms , Stuart balanced a peacock feather both horizontally and vertically , lost it , caught it again , and then played an minuet , probably on a lute . [ 2 ]

#Text=In December 1771 , Nürenbach founded the first public theater in Oslo , composed of a small theater staff of stage performers , of which he and Stuart where probably the only artists with previous professional training and experience .
#Text=While the theater 's activity is mostly unknown , Stuart was likely the actress acting with Nürenbach in the play Jomfru Pecunia by M. Nissen .
#Text=In February 1772 , the theater was evidently closed and Nürenbach left for Sweden .
#Text=Later life
#Text=Stuart herself left for Sweden in 1774 , and she is known to have performed in Gothenburg in April 1774 . [ 2 ]
#Text=She is not mentioned after this .
#Text=In 1783 , a dancer by the name of Eleanore Stuart made her debut at the Royal Danish Theatre in Copenhagen ; she may have been the daughter of Christina Doreothea Stuart . [ 1 ]
